	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I'm bored and just decided to put something in.<BR>
Everything seemed fine until Kunrak and it's beyond level 60 came in. Then the problems started.<BR>
First it was the hybrids complaining that their classes were too underpowered compared to their counterparts.<BR>
Now it's the casters whom have that annoying resistance and spellbook to deal with.<BR>
New spells for the casters are a great idea I think, as the melee classes get new armor all the time, though I wish the armor would actually help reduce damage more rather than seem to raise your agility.<BR>
Here's what I think about the classes. good/bad<BR>
<BR>
Warrior: Gets best blade and best armor and very good skills/gets boring to play after a while until level 50+, very boring to sit and wait for your HP to heal<BR>
<BR>
Monk: Alot of skills, best damage dealers, not money grubbers as they were designed for/no true flaws in the class yet<BR>
<BR>
Rogue:Get the single most powerful melee attack, get sneak and hide, pretty much like a ninja or theif/somewhat a group dependant class due to backstab, but groups are a good thing<BR>
<BR>
Bard: mana free songs that are useful just about anywhere and work better in groups/ I haven't heard a single complaint from any bard cause they're so versitle<BR>
<BR>
Shadowknight: A great damage dealer if you play your cards right, you get good melee and good magic useage and are ment to be feared/ on certain servers it's hard for them to group with druids to get ports<BR>
<BR>
Shaman: A good balanced class like the bard, you get somewhat good melee skills, spells of an enchanter and druid, get some nice armor and have some really good spells/ I haven't truly found a flaw with em yet<BR>
<BR>
Cleric: Best healers, can summon food and drink, can make you powerful and are somewhat decent to weak melee fighters, can wear plate and are great vs undead/ no speedy spells, and hopefuly ressurection will go down to 14 or somewhere.<BR>
<BR>
Paladin: weak to average healers, decent to good meleers, good all aroundness of offense and defense/ somewhat hard to get into groups but is mostly a roleplaying class, not a powerleveling class<BR>
<BR>
Magician (mage): get a pet for almost any situation (though why don't fire pets turn to air pets or die when they're in water?) can summon all needed resources and are second in direct damage to wizards/ no porting but their pets allow good protecting and a good tank<BR>
<BR>
Necromancer: Got that nice looking skeleton pet and are good at speading a slow pain rather than direct death/ if they didn't have the pet they'd be more group dependant then they already are, in order to play a necromancer, you need to be patient.<BR>
<BR>
Enchanter: The class that has the best time when it isn't fighting. It's pet bites but is better than nothing. The enchanter is better as making money than it is at experience, can also charm enemies into pets which is very fun and can avoid battles with mind spells, can also turn itself into other things/ when making experience the enchanter is very group dependant<BR>
<BR>
Druid: known as the traveling class, can charm animals for pets, can do some decent buffs as well as being able to cammo and go faster than any other class anywhere/get bugged for ports and speed all the time and get weak armor but they wern't ment to get into battle, more like being able to run from it with their speed.<BR>
<BR>
Ranger: The battered bunch of the century, if it wern't for spells like snare and root, they'd be even worse than they are now. They get good melee stats and very bad armor stats (until they get speed to run away) /bow useage isn't too useful until arrows are made a little cheaper, they can't self port, and most of the good mobs are easy to find.<BR>
<BR>
Beastmaster: That pet there is a lifesaver for the class as it's mostly dependant on it, plus it's able to zone too. Uses monk gear and has bad armor, although the pet is the tank. A well balanced class overall/ it wasn't able to use soft wicker before :P<BR>
<BR>
Wizards: Best direct damage dealers in the game and can teleport to places as well as translocate people so they don't need to waste more mana/ the constant resistance is the only thing that keeps this class from being the most fun. Maybe if there were items to make it's spells hit more commonly, then they would be more happy, and hopefully that's what being done.<BR>
<BR>
So overall here's what I think should be inproved:<BR>
Warriors: Give em some good animations for taunting or something to make the class more interesting.<BR>
Monks: No real fix ups needed here<BR>
Rogues: Give en a poison with a snare effect<BR>
Bard: again, no real changes<BR>
Shadowknights: Maybe the 'kick' ability or a instill doubt ability would be good from them or giving them to their pets instead would make the pets more useful<BR>
Shamans: Give them the ability to make weak potions from the start<BR>
Clerics: That ressurection spell at a lower level will be helpful<BR>
Paladins: 'kick' maybe be useful here as well, and perhaps the paladin should have a proc vs undead that grows once you reach certain seasons, (and equiping a sword such as the ghoulbane would double the times the proc activates) but the rez spell is useful never the less.<BR>
Magicians: Give em a spell to give their pets a few extra abilities. They don't truly need porting spells (though that may change once norrath continues to grow)<BR>
Necromancers: Because they're weak meleers, give them the instill doubt ability so maybe they might think of using their weapons a little more often.<BR>
Enchanters: Power up their pets or make them a little more useful<BR>
Druids: I can't think of any true changes other than maybe translocation<BR>
